name: Gadi Evron
text: @falconsview I challenge that our fundamentals in security are technical. That has failed is. I believe they are strategic.

name: Gadi Evron
text: @falconsview Even if I'm wrong, your way (everyone's current way) has already failed.

name: Gadi Evron
text: @falconsview Disagree again. Our current basics are about building well, maintaining, and detecting. In the asymmetrical landscape we live in that can't succeed. Assuming everything is broken and building security to work is the approach to take. Then spending some time on the basics.

name: Gadi Evron
text: @falconsview So if no one has the ability or will to do it, and never have, how is this still the thing to do? We have failed as an industry.

name: Gadi Evron
text: @falconsview All these fortune 100s had everything down, as far as is feasible. It always breaks down anyway. It's not working for us. I'm not saying we don't need it, but if it hadn't saved us yet, it won't.

name: Gadi Evron
text: @falconsview What are foundational practices?

name: Gadi Evron
text: @falconsview I disagree, the basics have proven to never be in place. Build assuming there are no basics, as that is the truth. (Invest in them, but they won't solve your problems)

name: Gadi Evron
text: Okay, one more thing, tactical. Make IT your friends. Help them solve their problems like that ancient legacy system they need to build a new platform around, and it will solve some of your problems, and you'll gain an ally.

name: Gadi Evron
text: @maxsec Shadow IT happens because people want to get the job done. It's always going to be an issue. But we can mitigate it by helping them do this.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Lastly, stop buying stuff that's useless like you have been doing for decades. Unless you must have it for compliance, of course. Try getting more people, or investing in a new product from a baby startup. Learning along with them will get you results.

name: Gadi Evron
text: With bias on my end, you and your team should attend ACoD. You will get out full of ideas, friends, and things you can take home and do to improve. //t.co/OBWF8n1Jwt - registration opens in September.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Most importantly, stop talking about information sharing. We are doing the best we can. Stop paying for overpriced conferences, and send your people to be trained.

name: Gadi Evron
text: If you don't have direct access to management, a budget, and can shield your people from corporate b/s. You're in the wrong job, leave that place.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Build a really solid IR capability. At the end of the day it's the only thing we truly do well. And, IR people are in the trenches. They are your human sensors.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Learn what it means to be a business enabler. Become a business driver, not a cost center.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Hire remotely, it's the only way you can get the team you need.

name: Gadi Evron
text: The basics have failed us. They matter, make them a control, but look for new ways of doing things.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Demand your vendors do what you could even expect before. Be effective if a 0day happens. Detect 0days. Detect attacks, not just events. Be effective after being bypassed. Be agnostic to stupid users and flat, patch-less network.

name: Gadi Evron
text: That was #3, oops.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Start a security program, any program, and stick to it. You can add in more outlooks such as the kill chain or Att&ck, but work within a framework. Make sure it creates a language from board-level to a level 1 analyst. Make sure it looks at Threat, Environment, and Impact.

name: Gadi Evron
text: 2. Hire people who will micro-innovate for you. Hunters, secdevops, whatever. Find challenges and code around them.

name: Gadi Evron
text: 1. Innovate. Most of us talk about it, and yet most of us have no capacity, budget, or organizational willingness to innovate.

name: Gadi Evron
text: But things are not all doom and gloom. We can in fact do better.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Worst of all, we know that no matter what we do, we are going to fail. Fun going to work every day with that mindset, isn't it?

name: Gadi Evron
text: The attackers can download our tools, change a couple of bits, and bypass our defenses. They also have nearly no negative incentives to act. Most of us don't look at that, we act in our Bias to Action, looking to firefight.

name: Gadi Evron
text: We look to new threats as the center of attention, and much the same look to silver bullets, even if we have programs in place to test either against. Why did none of us except at the bleeding edge, seek zero trust last year? Meh.

name: Gadi Evron
text: We are built to slow down the business and be a cost center, and often the ones forcing more friction on functionality.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Our most effective control is incident response. We know we are going to get pwned. If we are lucky enough to discover it ourselves, and before it's in the press, we can then mitigate the damage.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Our users are stupid, and our environments are insecure. We have very little visibility even if we work on it for years, and our intelligence programs trying to get ahead of the problems are often looking at someone else's data. No information or knowledge.

name: Gadi Evron
text: We need to succeed every time, they need to succeed only once.

name: Gadi Evron
text: We face an asymmetry where the attacker is stronger, faster, needs less budget, and is maneuverable. We are none of these.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Whenever a data breach happens we be the basics. There are always going to be an unpatched machine or a default password. Large enterprises are difficult to defend, and at 2019, defending yourself is often an act just to do something as we are built to fail.

text: @fsmontenegro @anton_chuvakin @MaorFranco @s_crawford @swagitda_ @apbarros @ctcrandall @haroonmeer The attacker works on the API level, the user on the GUI. text: * Gun ports were open as a sign of respect, which humanity had no way of knowing ** Their sensors are so powerful, they disable the human ship's engines, but you don't know that.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Naturally, with the war nearly destroying the Earth and with so many dead, the captain can be seen as nothing else than an idiot at best, and a traitor at worst. But putting such social aspects aside... You're now in the captain's shoes - do you not open fire? Mind. Blown.

name: Gadi Evron
text: Now, I ask you - if you are the human captain, isn't opening fire the only reasonable choice to make?

name: Gadi Evron
text: Here is the chronology of events, in quick succession: First, an unknown and powerful enemy ship is encountered in potentially hostile territory. Second, the ship approaches with gun ports* open. Third, they quickly follow up and disable** your engines.

name: Gadi Evron
text: That said, today Jonathan Braverman enlightened me.

name: Gadi Evron
text: When humans encountered the Minbari and started the Earth-Minbari War, the only real option the captain had was to open fire. Having watched the show many times, I followed the narrative that the human captain panicked and fired needlessly. I never considered another option.

text: (3) Be effective even if bypassed. Why should an attacker be able to operate with impunity if they manage to bypass your tool? [4/7]

name: Gadi Evron
text: #3 should start differently: Be effective even if bypassed. Why should an attacker be able to operate with impunity if they manage to bypass your tool?

name: Gadi Evron
text: And an extra one for vendor behavior, rather than product: Take the burden to not become shelfware after deployment. If you are not deployed, fully used (as needed), and pushing your customer to deploy - you should be kicked out. [7/7]

name: Gadi Evron
text: (5) Share data with other products. Augment them. If you see something, another tool should be able to use it to perform better as well. It's about the customer's value, not competition. [6/7]

name: Gadi Evron
text: (4) Detect real attackers, not signs that might indicate an attack. Do it with high fidelity. Don't be a noise generator! [5/7]

name: Gadi Evron
text: (2) Be 0day agnostic - detect the unknown unknowns. It's time we stopped accepting tools which detect mostly only the known, as we don't have high expectations and grew kind of used to mediocrity. [3/7]

name: Gadi Evron
text: (1) Don't be vulnerable to the attacker's lab (they download you, research you, change 2 bits in their attack... and bypass you) [2/7]
